# we may assume that the popular is more than 0.383856 (50%) (from describe output) 
popular = df.popularity > 0.383856
notpopular = df.popularity < 0.383856
In [108]:
# discover director impact on the popularity, sample from 0:50
plt.figure(figsize=[20,22])
df.director[popular].value_counts()[0:50].plot(kind='bar',alpha=0.5, color='blue', label='popular')
df.director[notpopular].value_counts()[0:50].plot(kind='bar',alpha=0.5, color='red', label='notpopular')
plt.legend()
plt.title('Directors impact on the popularity')
plt.xlabel('Director Name')
plt.ylabel('Popularity')

In [101]:
# check budget effect on the popularity
def histogram(budget):
    budget[popular].hist(alpha=0.5, bins=20, label='popular')
    budget[notpopular].hist(alpha=0.5, bins=20, label='notpopular')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('budget effect on the popularity')
    plt.xlabel('budget')
    plt.ylabel('Popularity')
    
histogram(df["budget"])
Observation : High budget movies are not necessairly the most poular movies.¶

The year of release has a slight effect on the popularity¶

The vote count has a slight effect on the popularity¶

It seems that 120-130 minutes is the most prefered time which reflected postively on the poularity¶

Observation : vote count has no significant impact on the popularity¶

Conclusions¶

  • The year of release has a slight effect on the popularity.
  • The vote count has a slight effect on the popularity.
  • directors not affecting the popularity significantly
  • It seems that 120-130 minutes is the most prefered time which reflected postively on the poularity.
  • genres and production companies has the most significant impact on the popularity

limitations: it will be helpful if there is more data about vote count to be by gender and age which will give more reflection for the reason of selection and voting.
